{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17480699","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17480699"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T23:49:30+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T23:49:30+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"96"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"96","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/96"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.18,0.41,0.07,0.08,0.26]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"96"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"111028"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"96","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/96"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"96"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"93145"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1028"},{"type":"tags","id":"1984"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4962"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"13909"},{"type":"contributions","id":"30599"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"111028","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/111028"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 27-year-old woman presents to her General Practitioner with a three week history of fatigue, generalised weakness, dizziness, and intermittent palpitations. She reports no particular timing of symptoms, no relation to exertion or eating, and no previous similar episodes. She reports recent intentional weight loss of 5kg, having started an intermittent fasting diet a few months ago due to concerns her weight was starting to rise again following initial losses after a gastric bypass two years ago. She last ate four hours ago.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHer medical history is significant for anxiety and depression. Her regular medications include escitalopram and the oral contraceptive pill. She works as a registered nurse at the local hospital. She is a non-smoker and drinks alcohol socially. She lives with her sister, who has coeliac disease and type 1 diabetes.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe physical examination is unremarkable. Her BMI is 26. Finger-prick testing reveals a capillary glucose level of 2.9 mmol/L (normal 4 \u2013 7 mmol/L). The GP contacts the tertiary hospital and on their advice a panel of bloods are sent, and the below results are later returned. In the meantime she receives 100mL of oral glucose solution and her blood glucose normalises.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPlasma glucose: 3.1 mmol/L (4 \u2013 7 mmol/L)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHbA1c: 5.1% (\u0026lt;6.5%)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPlasma insulin: 394 pmol/L (\u0026lt;170 pmol/L)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPro-insulin: 4.5 pmol/L (3 \u2013 20 pmol/L)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EC-peptide: 670 pmol/L (350- 1400 pmol/L)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which of the following diagnoses is most consistent with the above picture?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Dumping syndrome","Factitious hypoglycaemia","Intermittent fasting","Impaired insulin sensitivity","Insulinoma"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe patient has presented with non-specific symptoms that snap into focus when the low blood glucose level is identified, representing autonomic (palpitations) and neuroglycopaenic features (dizziness, weakness, fatigue) of\u00a0\u003Cstrong\u003Ehypoglycaemia\u003C/strong\u003E. Although her history includes aspects that raise the possibility of the alternative differentials offered, her laboratory results indicate the presence of exogenous insulin consistent with\u00a0\u003Cstrong\u003Efactitious hypoglycaemia\u003C/strong\u003E.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EEndogenous insulin synthesis occurs in the pancreatic beta cells in response to hyperglycaemia, beginning as pro-insulin that is subsequently cleaved into insulin and c-peptide. Therefore, c-peptide is a concomitant by-product of endogenous insulin production, even in the case of neoplastic proliferation of beta cells such as insulinoma. Accordingly, in this case, the mismatch between elevated insulin level and normal pro-insulin and c-peptide suggests the insulin\u2019s source must be exogenous.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EFactitious hypoglycaemia is an uncommon condition that can occur in both diabetic and non-diabetic patients, and generally refers to the surreptitious use of insulin or insulin secretagogues (though accidental self-administration or malicious administration by others is also recognised). Studies demonstrate that it occurs more commonly in women in their 20s \u2013 30s, in those with access to insulin (medical professionals, close contacts of diabetics, etc), and those with a history of psychiatric disorders.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EInsulinoma, impaired insulin sensitivity, and dumping syndrome are all examples where endogenous hyperinsulinaemia can be observed, however in each of these conditions the relationship between insulin and c-peptide levels is preserved. Intermittent fasting, while potentially associated with hypoglycaemia during fasting periods, would not provoke an insulinaemic response.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Surreptitious insulin use should always be considered in cases of unexplained hypoglycaemia."],"references":["Kandaswamy L, Raghavan R, Pappachan JM. Spontaneous hypoglycemia: diagnostic evaluation and management. Endocrine. 2016 Jul;53(1):47-57."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"93145"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"96"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"93145","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/93145"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-08-07T08:34:10+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-08-07T08:34:10+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"96"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"111028"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"65","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/65"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Investigations","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"76","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/76"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level II","synonyms":null,"description":"Understand (interpreting and summarizing information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"